By symmetry,
\[BP = BP^\prime = \frac{BC}{2 \cos \angle BCP}\]and
\[AP = AP^\prime = \frac{AB}{2 \cos \angle ACP}\]for some point $P^\prime.$

In order to minimize $AP + BP,$ we should have ||
\begin{align*}
2 \cos \angle ACP &= 2 \cos \angle BCP \\
\cos \angle ACP &= \cos \angle BCP \\
\angle ACP &= \angle BCP.
\end{align*}Thus, a possible location for $P$ is where the two circles intersect.

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABC,$
\begin{align*}
AB^2 &= 10^2 + 1^2 - 2 \cdot 10 \cdot 1 \cos \alpha \\
BC^2 &= 1^2 + 3^2 - 2 \cdot 1 \cdot 3 \cos (180^\circ - \alpha) = 10^2 + 3^2 + 2 \cdot 10 \cdot 3 \cos \alpha \\
AC^2 &= 10^2 + 1^2 + 2 \cdot 10 \cdot 1 \cos \alpha,
\end{align*}so $\cos \alpha = \frac{17}{20}$ (because $\cos (180^\circ - \alpha) = -\cos \alpha$).

Hence,
\[\cos \angle ACP = \cos \angle BCP = \frac{4}{5}.\]Also, $AP = \frac{AB}{2 \cos \angle ACP} = \frac{20}{8} = \frac{5}{2},$ and $BP = BC + CP \cos \angle BCP = 2 + 5 \cdot \frac{4}{5} = 6.$  Therefore, $AP + BP = \frac{5}{2} + 6 = \frac{17}{2}.$

Therefore, $m + n = \boxed{19}.$

