output:
By the Triangle Inequality, a triangle with side lengths $7$, $10$, and $x^2$ exists if and only if \begin{align*}
10 + 7 &> x^2 \quad\Rightarrow \\
17 &> x^2 \quad\Rightarrow \\
\sqrt{17} &> x
\end{align*}and \begin{align*}
7 + x^2 &> 10 \quad\Rightarrow \\
x^2 &> 3 \quad\Rightarrow \\
x &> \sqrt{3}
\end{align*}Therefore, the triangle exists if and only if $\sqrt{3} < x < \sqrt{17},$ where $x$ is an integer. The integers between $\sqrt{3}$ and $\sqrt{17}$ are $2,3,4$, and $5,$ so the positive integer values of $x$ are $\boxed{2,3,4,5}.$

Instead of using numerical values, we can write $64$ as $4^3$ and then use the rules of logarithms: \begin{align*}
\log_4 64 &= \log_4 (4^3) \\
&= \boxed{3}.
\end{align*}

