By completing the square, we obtain $(x+a/2)^2 = a^2/4+14$. The left hand side is a square, so the right hand side must be as well. In other words, $a^2/4+14 = m^2$ for some positive integer $m$. Rearranging, $a^2 = 4m^2 - 4 \cdot 14 = 4(m^2-14)$. Since both sides are even, $a$ must be even, say $a = 2b$ for some positive integer $b$. Substituting, $4b^2 = 4(m^2-14)$, or $b^2 = m^2-14$. By writing $m$ and $b$ as their prime factorizations \begin{align*}
m &= p_1^{e_1}p_2^{e_2}\cdots p_r^{e_r}\\
b &= q_1^{f_1}q_2^{f_2}\cdots q_s^{f_s}
\end{align*}and plugging in, we have \[\left(q_1^{f_1}q_2^{f_2}\cdots q_s^{f_s}\right)^2 = \left(p_1^{e_1}p_2^{e_2}\cdots p_r^{e_r}\right)^2 - 14.\]Since $m \neq b$, the prime factors of $m^2-14$ are all greater than $1$. The prime factors of $b^2$ are either the $p_i$'s, each with an even exponent, or an extra prime factor of $2$. Thus, the prime factorization of $m^2-14$ contains only prime factors of $m^2-14$. But we can add more factors of $m^2-14$ to the left hand side by inserting factors of $14$ on the right. Therefore, we must have $m^2-14 = 2^{2g+1}\cdot\text{odd}^2$ for some positive integer $g$. In other words, $m^2-14$ is $2$ times an odd integer squared. Re-arranging, $2^{2g+1}\cdot\text{odd}^2 - 14 = q_1^{f_1}q_2^{f_2}\cdots q_s^{f_s}$. But the right hand side is even, so the left hand side must be as well. Therefore, $\text{odd}^2$ must be even, which is only possible if $\text{odd}$ is even. Write $\text{odd} = 2d$, so $2^{2g+1}\cdot (2d)^2 = q_1^{f_1}q_2^{f_2}\cdots q_s^{f_s} + 14$. Rearranging, $2^{2g+1}d^2 = \frac{1}{4}\left(q_1^{f_1}q_2^{f_2}\cdots q_s^{f_s} + 14\right)$. The right hand side is an integer, so $4|2d^2$, which implies $2|d$. Write $d=2d'$ for some positive integer $d'$. Substituting, $2^{2g-1}d'^2 = \frac{1}{4} \left(q_1^{f_1}q_2^{f_2}\cdots q_s^{f_s} + 14\right)$. Since both $2^{2g-1}$ and $d'^2$ are integers, the right hand side must be a multiple of $2^{2g-1}$. This requires that $4|\left(q_1^{f_1}q_2^{f_2}\cdots q_s^{f_s} + 14\right)$. This is only possible if $q_1^{f_1}q_2^{f_2}\cdots q_s^{f_s}$ is a multiple of $4$, which requires at least one of the $f_i$'s to be greater than $1$. But this is impossible since the $q_i$'s are all different primes. Therefore there are no solutions in positive integers $a,b$, so the answer is $\boxed{0}$.

We could do the multiplication first and then the addition, or we could apply the distributive property and then the addition. We will do the former, using the distributive property. \begin{align*}
