Since $f(b)=4$, we have that $f^{-1}(f(b))=f^{-1}(4)$. But since $f^{-1}(f(x))=x$ for all $x$, we must have $b=f^{-1}(4)$. Therefore, $b$ is the $y$-coordinate of the point where the graph of $y=f^{-1}(x)$ intersects the line $x=4$. This point is given by $\left(4,f^{-1}(4)\right)$. Therefore, $b=f^{-1}(4)$.

By symmetry of the graph of $y=f(x)$ and $y=f^{-1}(x)$ over the line $y=x$, we find that $a$ is the $x$-coordinate of the point where the graph of $y=f^{-1}(x)$ intersects the line $y=4$. Therefore, $a$ is the $x$-coordinate of $\left(4,f^{-1}(4)\right)$. Thus, $a=4$.

Since $a=4$ and $b=f^{-1}(4)$, we have $a-b=4-b=4-f^{-1}(4)=f(b)-b=4-4=\boxed{0}$.

