When we expand $(x-2)(x+2)(x^2+4)$, we must distribute each binomial to each of the other two binomials. We start with the first two binomials: \begin{align*}
(x-2)(x+2)&=(x)(x)+(x)(2)+(-2)(x)+(-2)(2)\\
&=x^2 +2x-2x-4\\
&=\boxed{x^2-4}.
\end{align*}Now, we can multiply $(x^2-4)(x^2+4)$: \begin{align*}
(x^2-4)(x^2+4)&=(x^2)(x^2)+(x^2)(4)+(-4)(x^2)+(-4)(4)\\
&=x^4+4x^2-4x^2-16\\
&=x^4-16.
\end{align*}

We have $64 = 2^6$, so we can rewrite the equation as  \[2^n\cdot 4^n=(2^6)^{n-36}.\]Using the property $(a^m)^n=a^{mn}$, we can simplify the equation as follows:  \begin{align*}
2^n\cdot 4^n&=2^{6(n-36)},
\\\Rightarrow\qquad (2^n)^1\cdot(2^n)^2&=2^{6n-36\cdot 6},
\\\Rightarrow\qquad 2^n\cdot 2^{2n}&=2^{6n-216},
\\\Rightarrow\qquad 2^{n+2n}&=2^{6n-216}.
\end{align*}Since $2^{n+2n}=2^{3n}$, the equation simplifies to \[2^{3n} = 2^{6n-216}.\]Then we can set the exponents equal to each other and solve for $n$: \begin{align*}
3n &= 6n-216,
\\\Rightarrow\qquad -3n &= -216,
\\\Rightarrow\qquad n &= \boxed{72}.
\end{align*}

Since we want to solve for $(u, v),$ we see that it is necessary to eliminate the variable $v.$ To do this, we can multiply the first equation by 2 and the second equation by $-1,$ so that we have the same coefficient for $v.$ Multiplying the first equation by 2 gives \begin{align*}
2\cdot5u&=2\cdot(-7-2v),\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 10u&=-14-4v.
\end{align*}Multiplying the second equation by $-1$ gives  \begin{align*}
-1\cdot3u&=-1\cdot(4v-25),\\
\Rightarrow\qquad -3u&=-4v+25.
\end{align*}Using the distributive property and combining like terms gives  \begin{align*}
10u&=-14-4v,\\ -3u&=-4v+25.
\end{align*}Thus, we have $-4v$ equal to $-4v$ in each equation, so we can set the two expressions equal to each other \[-14-4v=-4v+25.\]Simplifying gives $14=25,$ which is obviously false. Therefore, there must be no solution to the system of equations. Thus, there is $\boxed{\text{no solution}}$ to the system of equations.

Instead of writing out the full sequence, we consider the exponents of $2$ in each term of sequence $A:$
\[2^1,2^2,2^3,2^4,2^5,\ldots.\]Meanwhile, sequence $B$ is an arithmetic sequence with common difference $20:$
\[20\cdot1,20\cdot2,20\cdot3,20\cdot4,20\cdot5,\ldots.\]The first term in sequence $A$ that is larger than the first term in sequence $B$ is $2^5=32,$ while the second term of sequence $B$ is $20\cdot2=40.$ Therefore, the answer is $\boxed{32-40=-8}.$ [asy]
